{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use British English|date=August 2015}} {{coord|51|31|25|N|0|7|59|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}} {{refimprove|date=February 2017}} [[File:Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology and the Science Library, Malet Place]] The '''Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology''' in [[London]] is part of [[University College London]] Museums and Collections. The museum contains over 80,000 objects and ranks among some of the world's leading collections of Egyptian and Sudanese material.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://petriecat.museums.ucl.ac.uk/|title=UCL Petrie Museum Online Catalogue|website=petriecat.museums.ucl.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>
==History== <!--DO NOT PASTE IN GENERAL BOOK REFERENCES WITHOUT PAGE NUMBERS THAT SIMPLY SUPPORT THE EXISTENCE OF THE INDIVIDUALS WHOSE NAMES APPEAR; SOURCES ARE TO SUPPORT **SPECIFIC** FACTUAL CONTENT OF SENTENCES, THE PUBLISHED WHO, WHAT, WHEN, WHERE, WHY FACTS THAT ARE PRESENTED IN EACH SENTENCE.--> [[File:Upper part of a statuette of an Egyptian man and his wife. 18th Dynasty. From Egypt. From the Amelia Edwards Collection. Now housed in the Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology, London.jpg|thumb|Upper part of a statuette of an Egyptian woman and her husband. 18th Dynasty. From Egypt. From the Amelia Edwards Collection. Now housed in the Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology, London]] The museum was established as a teaching resource for the Department of [[Egypt]]ian [[Archaeology]] and [[Philology]] at University College at the same time as the department was established in 1892.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://museum-mile.org.uk/ucl-petrie-museum|title=UCL: The Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology - Museum Mile|website=museum-mile.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> The initial collection was donated by the writer [[Amelia Edwards]].<ref>Moon, Brenda E. (2006). ''More Usefully Employed: Amelia B. Edwards, Writer, Traveller and Campaigner for Ancient Egypt,'' London: Egypt Exploration Society.{{full|date=February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| author = Willey, Russ | date = 24 November 2014 | title = Rehumanising the past. Petrie Museum, behind Gower Street, Bloomsbury | location = London, ENG | publisher=Hidden London [Russ Willey] | url=http://hidden-london.com/the-guide/petrie-museum/ | access-date=24 November 2014}}</ref> The first Edwards Professor, [[William Matthew Flinders Petrie]], conducted many important excavations, and in 1913 he sold his collections of Egyptian antiquities to University College, creating the Flinders Petrie Collection of Egyptian Antiquities, and transforming the museum into one of the leading collections outside Egypt. Petrie excavated dozens of major sites in the course of his career, including the Roman Period cemeteries at Hawara<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/ThePetrieMuseumOfEgyptianArchaeology|title=The Petrie Museum Of Egyptian Archaeology|last=Alice Stevenson|first=UCL Press|date=2015-06-04}}</ref>, famous for the beautiful mummy portraits in classical Roman style<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/press/exhibitions/2000/ancient-faces-mummy-portraits-from-roman-egypt|title=https://www.metmuseum.org/press/exhibitions/2000/ancient-faces-mummy-portraits-from-roman-egypt|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>;<ref name = IncompletePicton>{{cite book | author = [Unknown author] | date = 2007 | editors = Picton, Janet; Quirke,, Stephen & Roberts, Paul C. | chapter = [Unknown chapter] | title = Living Images: Egyptian Funerary Portraits in the Petrie Museum | page = | location = Walnut Creek, CA | publisher = Left Coast Press | isbn = | url = | access-date = | quote = }}{{full|date=February 2017}}</ref> Amarna, the city of king Akhenaten;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amarnaproject.com/pages/amarna_the_place/central_city/index.shtml|title=The Central City - Amarna The Place - Amarna Project|website=www.amarnaproject.com|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> and the first true pyramid, at Meydum, where he uncovered some of the earliest evidence for mummification.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/culture/node/21/about|title=UCL - London's Global University|last=UCL|website=UCL CULTURE|language=en|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>
The collection and library were arranged in galleries within the university and a guidebook published in 1915. Initially, the collection's visitors were students and academics; it was not then open to the general public. Petrie retired from University College London (UCL) in 1933, though his successors continued to add to the collections, excavating in other parts of Egypt and the Sudan. During the [[Second World War]] (1939–1945) the collection was packed up and moved out of London for safekeeping. In the early 1950s it was moved into a former stable, where it remains adjacent to the science library of UCL.
==Current description== [[File:On either side of this small and narrow hall, there are displaying cases, containing fragments and slabs of stelae. This is seen immediately after you pass through the information desk.JPG|thumb|left|Fragments and slabs of stelae]]
The museum is at Malet Place, near [[Gower Street (London)|Gower Street]] and the University College London science library. Admission is free, and as of January 2018 the museum is open each afternoon 1pm-5pm, Tuesday to Saturday, with researchers accommodated at other times as well.<ref name="Petrie Museum">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/culture/petrie-museum | title=Petrie Museum | first=|last=Petrie Museum Staff|work=ucl.ac.uk | access-date=6 January 2018}}</ref>
The museum has an education programme for adults and families,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/culture/events/get-hands-ancient-egypt-0|title=Get Hands on with ancient Egypt|last=UCL|website=UCL CULTURE|language=en|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> and has an active Friends organisation allowing members to attend lectures, museum seminars, tours to Egypt and Egyptian collections, social events, and so on. As well, the Friends raise funds towards the conservation, publication and display of the Petrie Museum's outstanding collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/FriendsofPetrie/pages/Membership.html|title=Friends of the Petrie Museum Membership|author=Petrie Museum Staff|date=28 February 2017|work=Petrie.UCL.ac.uk | accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref>
===Organisation and collections=== [[File:You will see this displaying case when you immediately enter into the Museum; it is next to the information desk. There are many figurines and statuettes.JPG|thumb|Display case at entrance to the Petrie, with figurines and statuettes.]] The museum is split into three galleries, with the main gallery (housed above the old stables) containing many of the museum's small artifacts, as well as tablets of writing and mummy portraits and cases. Another gallery contains mainly pottery. The third is along a stairwell down to an emergency exit. Some parts of the collection are not lit to protect light-sensitive items, and torches (flashlights) are supplied to see inside the cases.
The collection has been digitised and the catalogue can be browsed and consulted online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petriecat.museums.ucl.ac.uk/search.aspx|title=UCL Petrie Museum Online Catalogue|author=Petrie Museum Staff|date=28 February 2017|work=Petrie.UCL.ac.uk | accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref>
===Notable holdings=== The collection contains some significant 'firsts': one of the earliest pieces of linen from Egypt (about 5000 BC); two lions from the temple of Min at Koptos, from the first group of monumental sculpture (about 3000 BC, these are located in the main UCL building); a fragment from the first kinglist or calendar (about 2900 BC); the earliest example of metal from Egypt, the first worked iron beads; the earliest example of glazing; the earliest 'cylinder seal' in Egypt (about 3500 BC); the oldest wills on papyrus paper; the oldest [[Kahun Gynecological Papyrus|gynaecological papyrus]]; the only veterinary papyrus from ancient Egypt; and the largest architectural drawing, showing a shrine (about 1300 BC).
Costume is another strength of the collection.<ref>{{cite book | author = Hall, Rosalind M. | date = 1986 | title = Egyptian Textiles | page = | location = | publisher = Shire Publications | isbn = | url = | access-date = | quote = }}{{full|date=February 2017}}</ref>{{verification needed|date=February 2017}}{{page needed|date=February 2017}} In addition to the 'oldest dress' there is a unique beadnet dress of a dancer from the Pyramid Age (about 2400 BC), two long sleeved robes of the same date, a suit of armour from the palace of Memphis, as well as socks and sandals from the Roman period. The collection contains works of art from Akhenaten’s city at Amarna: colourful tiles, carvings and frescoes, from many other important Egyptian and Nubian settlements and burial sites. The museum houses the world’s largest collection of Roman period mummy portraits (first to second centuries AD).<ref name = IncompletePicton/>{{page needed|date=February 2017}}
The collection also includes material from the Coptic and Islamic periods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/petrie/museumtrails |title=Trails and Resources |author=Petrie Museum Staff |date=2 March 2013 |work=Petrie.UCL.ac.uk |accessdate=28 February 2017 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302074838/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/petrie/museumtrails |archivedate= 2 March 2013 |df= }}</ref>
There is a substantial archive held in the museum, including excavation records, correspondence and photographs relating to excavations led by Flinders Petrie. There are additionally documents relating to the distribution of finds from fieldwork to museums worldwide between the 1887 and 1949. <ref>http://egyptartefacts.griffith.ox.ac.uk/</ref>
==Reputation== [[File:Interior of the Petrie Museum.JPG|thumb|right|Interior of the museum]] The museum contains over 80,000 objects and ranks among some of the world's leading collections of Egyptian and Sudanese material.<ref>https://www.ucl.ac.uk/culture/petrie-museum/about</ref> It only ranks behind the collections of the [[Cairo Museum]], [[British Museum|The British Museum]] and the [[Ägyptisches Museum]], Berlin in number and quality of items.{{says who?|date=February 2017}}{{cn|date=February 2017}}
==Published works== In 2015, the museum, in conjunction with UCL, published a multi-author compilation of articles, ''The Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology: Characters and Collections'', which is available in both print and via a free open access download.<ref name=CharactersAndCollections>{{cite book | editor = Stevenson, Alice | date = 2015 | title = The Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology: Characters and Collections | location = London, ENG | publisher = UCL Press | url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1468795/4/The_Petrie_Museum_of_Egyptian_Archaeology.pdf | accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> It is edited by [[Alice Stevenson (archaeologist)|Alice Stevenson]].
